'}]
commit_message:
Fix the os-extended-volumes key reference in the REST API history docs

The actual key in the response is os-extended-volumes:volumes_attached
so the REST API history doc needs to be updated for v2.3.

Change-Id: I17e8ddaf939718f737b3098357938ecd647e872c
Closes-Bug: #1511094

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-09-24 21:48:19.000000000', 'message': "Only create volumes with instance.az if cinder.cross_az_attach is False

Commit 6060888b58db42eea826939852838f9e1c204d2c changed the boot from
volume flow where source != 'volume' (where Nova creates the volume and
then attaches it to the instance during the server create operation)
such that the instance.availability_zone is always passed to the volume
create API.  That was done because if the cinder.cross_az_attach config
option is False then Nova requires the instance and volume AZs to be the
same when attaching the volume.

However, telling Cinder to create a volume based on the instance AZ can
fail if that AZ doesn't exist in Cinder.

Cinder commit b85d2812a8256ff82934d150dbc4909e041d8b31 works around this
by allowing Cinder to be configured to basically not fail if the
requested AZ does not exist. This is not a great solution though if you
have cinder.cross_az_attach=False in Nova because Cinder ignored your
request.  It's also terrible UX for the end user because they get a
NoValidHost when boot from volume fails.  There is a TODO in this change
to address that later (because exactly how cross-service AZs should work
is still being discussed).

This change addresses the gap introduced by always telling Cinder to
create the volume with the instance AZ.  We should only do that when
cinder.cross_az_attach is False, because that's the strict case where
Nova expects them to match.  If cross_az_attach is True, Nova doesn't
care what AZ the volume is in so we shouldn't try and accomodateforce
Cinder to accommodate the Nova AZ when creating the volume.

Closes-Bug: #1496235

Change-Id: I3d60c084fd71162a0d4835394f8e819723c1b8a7

commit_message:
Only create volumes with instance.az if cinder.cross_az_attach is False

Commit 6060888b58db42eea826939852838f9e1c204d2c changed the boot from
volume flow where source != 'volume' (where Nova creates the volume and
then attaches it to the instance during the server create operation)
such that the instance.availability_zone is always passed to the volume
create API.  That was done because if the cinder.cross_az_attach config
option is False then Nova requires the instance and volume AZs to be the
same when attaching the volume.

However, telling Cinder to create a volume based on the instance AZ can
fail if that AZ doesn't exist in Cinder.

Cinder commit b85d2812a8256ff82934d150dbc4909e041d8b31 works around this
by allowing Cinder to be configured to basically not fail if the
requested AZ does not exist. This is not a great solution though if you
have cinder.cross_az_attach=False in Nova because Cinder ignored your
request.  It's also terrible UX for the end user because they get a
NoValidHost when boot from volume fails.  There is a TODO in this change
to address that later (because exactly how cross-service AZs should work
is still being discussed).

This change addresses the gap introduced by always telling Cinder to
create the volume with the instance AZ.  We should only do that when
cinder.cross_az_attach is False, because that's the strict case where
Nova expects them to match.  If cross_az_attach is True, Nova doesn't
care what AZ the volume is in so we shouldn't try and force
Cinder to accommodate the Nova AZ when creating the volume.

Closes-Bug: #1496235

Change-Id: I3d60c084fd71162a0d4835394f8e819723c1b8a7

commit_message:
Declare multiattach is True in Dell Eqlx driver

An Eqlx volume can be attached to multi instances, however,
this feature is not declared in eqlx driver. As a result,
if a user create a multi-attached volume using eqlx as
backend, they will be failed.

In this commit, we declared multiattach is True in eqlx
driver.

Change-Id: Ia8e94e739c2573f1f26d8cb2713a6b851adf9428
Closes-Bug: #1519570

commit_message:
Add clients module to Tacker

We are invoking individual openstack clients everytime
we need it. But we need a generic openstack clients module
for code resuability. This patch does that by creating new clients.py
file in tacker/common.

Change-Id: Ibe06ff2eafa00b2825d5f412620cb4d051626164
Closes-Bug: #1518244

commit_message:
Sanity check for keystone

This runs first sanity check for keystone. After keystone is deployed
it checks tenants.list()

Change-Id: Ie919ffe6124eb70428309404a434d9b0eb0b9f70
Partially-Implements: blueprint sanity-check-container

commit_message:
Remove novaclient.v1_1 module

This reverts commit 036d42d7087a3c83a5feec0ad0a4c6af35df72c9

Once novaclient 2.34 is released we can merge this and
release as 3.0.0. The dependency is on the 2.34 release
request.

Change-Id: I1e3a8a8079b954fe60371c2d38ec23a10727c408

commit_message:
Fix metric-statistics doesn't respond "Conflict"

When metric-statistics without --merge_metrics is called
and which has multiple metrics matching metric name and dimensions,
it is expected to respond "409 Conflict" instead of
"500 Internal Server Error".

Change-Id: I26edf216b68385bf3bce11ba186d2b285b46874b
Closes-Bug: #1520061

(1 comment)

hey Ethan, thanks for putting this together. i have one question in-line, and a few more here.

i'm not sold on the idea of moving all the elements into the source tree with the python code, at least not in the same directory. if we ever move the plugins then we will need to move all the element code as well, is this the intention(to make it more modular)?

another alternative might be to have the plugins generate some sort of script that can be processed by sahara-image-elements, or similar. in this manner the plugin authors would be responsible for ensuring that their plugin would properly generate the "configuration" data for the image runner script. we might still collect all the elements in the sahara repo, and plugin authors would be responsible for generating new elements, but we could keep the elements separate from the python code. does this make sense with regards to the changes you are proposing?'}, {'account_id': 13953, 'date': '2015-11-23 23:03:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@elmiko: This is the first stage of a multi-spec effort, which I'm rolling out over the next few days (hopefully), but yes, it is my hope that eventually the image generation steps for each plugin can be reduced to something more 'pythonic', for lack of a better word, than elements, and that we can create a conversion mechanism to allow these to be interpreted either as elements or as scripts appropriate to other image generation tools. Early experiments indicate that this is broadly possible, with some sanitization of the current element set. But this is just step 1.

Mostly, in this spec, I want to make each plugin sovereign over its own image generation, so that versionitis between SIE and sahara's service can't happen, so that change between image gen mechanisms can occur gradually (that is, at all, given the scope of the task,) and so that when we do break the plugins into their own repos, they will encapsulate an entire flow (instead of half the flow, with image gen either in a common, still-monolithic repo, or nebulously defined in some non-scripted, ill-maintained doc somewhere.)"}, {'account_id': 13953, 'date': '2015-11-23 23:19:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 8932, 'date': '2015-11-24 01:49:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(2 comments)

Looks goods.I like the idea of getting rid of sahara-image-elements. It is a good start point so we can start discussing whether this is the best way to do it or even the best possible way to do it.'}, {'account_id': 13953, 'date': '2015-11-24 17:56:40.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 13953, 'date': '2015-11-24 17:59:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Telles: exactly. I actually *hope* that this spec gets punched a lot (and there are some ways I can imagine doing this that make deeper changes but are better, but I'm imagining an incremental approach toward those better ideas starting here, because Agile maybe.)

@Mike: I removed the forward-looking plan section, because I want to remove any spectre of "if I approve this patch, I'm approving the whole plan you lay out." Future specs are future specs.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-11-24 18:47:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

Ethan, i like this idea and i think the conversation surrounding it is interesting. i think we should discuss this further in the next team meeting (after the holiday).

i like the plugin authors having responsibility for owning the image generation code and i'm even ok with adding that code into the sahara repo. i'd like to discuss more about how we would express those images, i think the api endpoint is nice goal but i think we should also provide some sort of "offline" mechanism for creation as well.'}, {'account_id': 10670, 'date': '2015-11-25 20:40:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: -Code-Review

commit_message:
Move Image Generation Scripts into Plugins

As Sahara matures, it will be necessary to move framework-specific plugins
into their own repositories, maintaining a backward-compatible Sahara core
separately. As such, moving image generation logic into plugins is a
critical piece of and precondition for this abstraction effort.

Change-Id: I1db69fb9ea35d317a2e1baaaac1b8945973e2d0c
Describes: blueprint image-gen-into-plugins

commit_message:
Drop root for murano

Updates to ensure commands run in the murano containers
are done as the 'murano' user rather than root.

Change-Id: I558c46b032f11b83a9dc6b5abc158aa6d24ec0eb
Partially-Implements: blueprint drop-root

commit_message:
Added two precise Use Cases in the spec

The Watcher Decision Engine should query metrics from the Ceilometer 
API V2 to allow an easiest integration with OpenStack components
(especially DevStack).

Change-Id: I0d2dfd78925b1fa5e1d6b7629ced00a2943254a9

commit_message:
Add Google Container Registry to KubernetesCluster

Allow access to Google Container Registry using json key as
a password for docker login. The key is scoped to a specific
Google Cloud Platform Console project and its resources.
Add new field for key.

Partially implements: blueprint k8s-google-registry-support

Change-Id: Ica71d1a48ac7fb75a71497fcbe318d1b9e4e8192

commit_message:
Fix exception when doing volume set operation

The v2 SetVolume extends from show.ShowOne and returns None
after setting volume operation. It will raise an exception.
This patch is going to fix the issue by changing the parent
class of SetVolume to command.Command.

Change-Id: Iefa453fe4adad06f2a0601a052c01e74004be5b7
Closes-bug: 1521896

commit_message:
Provide a better comment for the object short-circuit

A previous commit was landed over a -1 from a core reviewer that was
concerned about the terse and flippant commit message that accompanied
the commit. The substance of that objection was that there was no good
explanation for why the change was made. Indeed, that why is likely
useful for people looking at the code too, so add a more complete
comment on the code in question.

Change-Id: I1ff777393502edf4ef3ed595e47bfcf73be0e5e8

commit_message:
Disable ceilometer-acompute in control node example

The ceilomter devstack plugin turns on every ceilometer service by
default. This disables the ceilometer-acompute service in the control
node example file.

Change-Id: Ic338350d5d1db266657e4bfd18b679cfff96b0e2

proxying my -1 from the previous change set.

I am worried we miss out BDM v2 here, for consistency.

Given cinder has a sharable flag, I am wondering why Nova needs an additional flag on the attachement.

Should we just assume any "shareable" cinder volume could be shared? Particularly when you consider its not just Nova that could be attaching to that volume, any more. (1 comment)

From the Cinder side - I agree with John. If we report the volume as shareable, it is safe to assume it can be shared by multiple instances. Really it doesn't matter on the Cinder side how many instances access the volume. We are just providing a data path between the backend storage and the host. If multiple instances on that host access the volume, it doesn't matter and the backend really has no idea.

The more interesting piece is when a volume is shared by multiple Nova hosts. In that case there needs to be multiple attachments to multiple separate initiators."}, {'account_id': 6804, 'date': '2015-11-28 18:42:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 12: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

I notice there's no mention of a config parameter to set an upper limit on the number of instances that can share the same volume. Hi All,

I reverted the spec to what we had in patch set #12 and also fixed comments from Walter and Scott.

The reason for the change is that it turned out that the original intention in Cinder was to handle attachments on instance level and the code was written with this mind set also, therefore it is the most straight forward way to start from there.

Later on we can consider refactoring the code in a way that Nova handles the terminate_connection call once when the connection does not have any attachments remaining on the given host. This changes should be transparent to the user. It will be added as a separate spec once it is decided to move to this direction.

For details of the discussion please check the IRC log here: http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/irclogs/%23openstack-cinder/%23openstack-cinder.2015-12-02.log.html
The discussion starts at 20:06 ("ildikov, ok back").

Thanks and Best Regards,

attaching a cinder volume to more than one instance.

Co-Authored-By: Krisztian Gacsal <krisztian.gacsal@ericsson.com>

bp multi_attach_volume

- gate-nova-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/74/188874/2/check/gate-nova-specs-python27/a5fcfbf/ : SUCCESS in 1m 48s'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-06-12 12:27:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(8 comments)

So this is the beginning of a great idea.

First a process piece, we need this approved in glance before we approve the work in Nova. I suspect you might need to do glance this cycle, and this work in the next cycle, but who know, we could get lucky.

We are trying to push a lot of this logic out of Nova, so it would be good to see if python-glanceclient could do most of the work of talking to barbican, etc. Cinder will need the same logic for when the create volumes from images, so it will have to be shared. oslo incubator style library owned by glance might be a good way forward (a bit like cinder's brick library).

On the specifics, I am not quite sure it delivers what you want. I think you might need a verification of the settings in glance, using a cert that related to the tenant id, or something like that to make man in the middle attack of glance harder. But that would involve some key exchange between barbican to trust what we get back from there, I guess.

... what I really mean is, might need to reduce the scope of what you claim to be fixing here, and possibly see about a way to tighten up the trust relationship, it looks a bit loose right now. I think storing some key in barbican thats specific to the tenant, and doing a signature on the glance metadata we access, might get us a step forward, assuming barbican is doing a trusted key exchange kind of system. Its possible you might want a compound key, with half in both places, or something like that, but thats probably going a bit too far."}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2015-06-16 12:51:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2015-06-16 12:51:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

The big thing I'd like see here is some acknowledgement of the fact that Nova already has LUKS support for encrypted disk images, and integration with that facility to avoid the need to decrypt images at all."}, {'account_id': 15524, 'date': '2015-06-16 17:16:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@John Garbutt: I agree with you that implementing some of this logic in python-glanceclient would allow other services to securely use this feature more easily, but I am unclear as to how that would work with Nova. Is there an immediate plan for Nova to shift from using v1 of the Glance API to the python-glanceclient? We also plan on further restricting the trust boundary by implementing Nova CLI options so that the user can provide the necessary information to verify an image (signature, public key uuid, etc). I think you are correct in saying that we need to take a step back on what we claim to be fixing. Under this spec, we really just hope to merge an initial, simpler feature. We intend to harden some of the known weaknesses under further specs. For example, we have considered mitigating issues with trusting the metadata by signing that as well.

@Daniel Berrange: In light of your comments and also those from John Garbutt, we will likely split this spec into at least two smaller specs; ostensibly, one will describe the image signing portion, and the other will describe the image encryption portion.'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2015-06-23 13:39:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

There is a hyper-v spec that is also looking at allowing upload of encrypted images

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/192892/4/specs/liberty/approved/hyper-v-shielded-vms.rst

This just further reinforces my view that we need a standard way to express the encryption format in the image metadata

eg, we might need

  img_encryption_format=block-aes|qcow2|luks|bitlocker|.....'}, {'account_id': 15524, 'date': '2015-06-23 21:14:01.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 15524, 'date': '2015-06-23 21:15:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 15524, 'date': '2015-06-23 21:19:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

As requested, I removed all references to image encryption. We will either propose a separate spec for that at a later date or wait for the progress on the  spec mentioned by Daniel Berrange. 

This spec is now solely focused on image signing, and we've included some minor updates to keep pace with John Garbutt's comments and suggestions."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-23 21:21:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

commit_message:
Nova Support of Glance Image Signing

This spec is related to work in the Glance project which handles
signed images.

SecurityImpact
DocImpact

Change-Id: Ia8e7fcc21d7c15e480facbe30af88cdce2d73159
Implements: blueprint nova-support-image-signing

commit_message:
Extend statistic benchmarks for Ceilometer

Existing benchmark scenario for statistics was not benchmark at all
it was check that statistic api works, now scenario was changed
with using new Ceilometer context and adding new configured
query parameters.

It allows to find a weak places in requesting Ceilometer data.

Change-Id: Iccde7422016e87f20237721b7fc1fb379646adf8

commit_message:
Pass environment variables of proxy to tox

When a development environment is under a proxy, tox is failed even if
environment variables of the proxy are set.

This problem has been solved on Tempest already.
This patch fixes this problem.

Change-Id: Ic0be1f8d6757ea57d8d12e463c467e83d7195794
Closes-Bug: #1465086

commit_message:
Remove cinderclient version pin

We had put this in because of the v2 version negotiation breaking public
clouds. That has since been fixed, and the pin here causes conflicts
with python-openstackclient.

Change-Id: I9ee2d9bfad36160ba41f65dcd657cbbca9f26050

commit_message:
Add functional tests for boot from volume

Test both that we can boot from volume from a pre-existing image
with and without auto-termination. Also that manually making the volume
from the image and then booting from it also works.

Also, add a cache invalidation that testing showed to be an issue.

Co-Authored-By: David Shrewsbury <shrewsbury.dave@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Removes unused arguments from modify/remove virt resources

Previously, the parent resource path was necessary in order
to properly modify / remove a virtual resource. This was needed
in the 'root/virtualization' namespace and sice we no longer
support it, we can safely remove it.

Change-Id: I28587537a04a5b4c9c4890a02d8343209ec1aa6e

This argument is unused and must be removed. Note that at the moment,
we don't check which instance is the disk actually attached to, as
this would involve extra unnecessary queries in the context this
method is used.

Change-Id: I1a7cb664c69e86e5823cab046b0a66b75ac722ea
"}]
commit_message:
Remove unused vm_name argument when checking if a disk is attached

This argument is unused and must be removed. Note that at the moment,
we don't check which instance is the disk actually attached to, as
this would involve extra unnecessary queries in the context this
method is used.

Change-Id: I1a7cb664c69e86e5823cab046b0a66b75ac722ea

method will raise a TypeError due to the fact that the exception

Change-Id: I8fa72adff1df9dc6abdcebc19323c6aae0c331d5
'}]
commit_message:
Fix utilsfactory unsupported class type exception

If the requested class type is not supported, the _get_class
method will raise a TypeError due to the fact that the exception
message is improperly formatted.

This patch fixes the issue and adds an unit test for this case.

Change-Id: I8fa72adff1df9dc6abdcebc19323c6aae0c331d5

commit_message:
Allow volume operations when shelved

Volume operations are allowed when an instance is
shutdown, paused and even soft deleted, but not when
shelved or shelved_offloaded. This spec will enable them
when shelved and shelved_offloaded as well.

Besides being useful in itself, this is also a first
step towards allowing operations on the boot volume
when shelved.

blueprint volume-ops-when-shelved
APIImpact
Change-Id: I52f32831bad5f5e1ff378c51186ee798dc3efa2e

commit_message:
Extend samples list benchmarks for Ceilometer

Existing benchmarks for samples list query are updated via new
context and adding new configured query parameters.

It allow to find a weak places in requesting Ceilometer data and extend
count of scenarios which use in Ceilometer.

Change-Id: If2c780ab6cf9a3bdfb339e9b96b34d909ff17f28

commit_message:
Move inheritance API spec into core Identity API

Remove the extension API doc, and integrate the OS-INHERIT APIs
into the main Identity API specification document. No changes to
the actual API URLs have been made.

Change-Id: Ia838dff1863b1b77472079b32783ae31557b1ef5
Implements: bp move-extensions

commit_message:
Compatibility with a coming puppet-heat fix

There is a fix coming into puppet-heat to ensure correct dependencies
within heat::keystone::domain class. This means the relationship with
Keystone_domain[heat_domain] will stop working. We should depend on the
whole class instead.

Change-Id: Ic541f11978908f9344e5590f3961f0d31c04bb0c
(cherry picked from commit 274925a1f138ede45eabb3aa10cbba137a67f834)

commit_message:
Remove optional keystoneauth1 imports

keystoneauth1 is now a hard dependency of os-client-config so there is
no way that this should not be importable.

Change-Id: I20901623e8b29f50d7ab1ed956472a4b1eda51bf

commit_message:
Revert "Wake up AMT interface before send request"

This is reported to not work as advertised, there's some contention over
the config name, and this was landed super close to a release. Revert it
until we can sort it out with more time.

This reverts commit 1ab3c9217edc8ebed7643f8ded7b16c39dd4bc70.

Change-Id: Iaeb36b30636a588d8d1984730d34ecb08c9596a8

/sys/devices/pci0000:20/0000:20:03.0/0000:21:00.2/net/ens2f2/ctlr_2/
host3/fc_host/host3

(cherry picked from commit 23e40d20ad86739d244119e879f55b6809fb96a7)

commit_message:
Parse FCoE sysfs device paths

FCoE devices have slightly different sysfs device paths to FC devices :

/sys/devices/pci0000:20/0000:20:03.0/0000:21:00.2/net/ens2f2/ctlr_2/
host3/fc_host/host3

As with FC devices we want the domain:bus:device.function of the device.
For FCoE devices this is listed prior to `net`.

Change-Id: I2e46af1679982964c0d90289bcf1a1fc702fcb15
(cherry picked from commit 23e40d20ad86739d244119e879f55b6809fb96a7)

commit_message:
Specify elasticsearch version to >=1.3.0,<2.0.0

Currently searchlight is using elasticsearch with version 1.x.x,
and 2.x is not supported yet. Need to restrict version less than
2.0.0 to make searchlight working properly.

Change-Id: I8a3b79b13cc12d508586f6e56d7a317dfd9a487b
Related-bug: #1515412

commit_message:
docs: remove duplicated section about error handling

There are two parts talk about error handling in nova api.
One is under general-info, and another one is under separated section
fault. This patch remove the empty one.

blueprint complete-todo-in-api-concept-doc

Change-Id: I4b9e79bf96fc5e8aa5a143f38a25e258a8be82f4

commit_message:
Remove get_server_group()

server_groups_client is not released yet on the latest temepst-lib
(v0.11.0), so we can remove get_server_group() because nobody uses
this method.

Change-Id: Ibc63c797fa72ac265ca72a0786071c458531b87d

I am concerned about sensitive data leaking into the profiling information. A lot of the comments mirror what was discussed with the keystone team when this integration was originally proposed against keystone (though that was pre-dating the specification process).'}, {'account_id': 3031, 'date': '2015-01-07 03:48:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(2 comments)'}, {'account_id': 688, 'date': '2015-01-07 13:27:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

Sorry, but I think this is a bad direction. I applaud the effort and understand the need for instrumentation, but the approach for instrumentation concerns me. 

We already have log messages in our code. We already have notification messages in our code. Now we're talking about introducing profiling messages in our code?

This same problem has been solved and proven in production with a monkey-patching approach similar to that used by New Relic and, for the python world, Tach [1] (and to a lesser extent Mock)

The monkey-patch approach simply introduces a loader in front of the executable. The necessary methods/functions are patched and the timings collected. 

Something like:

newosprofiler --config my_profiling_config my_program my_config

No code changes required and works across all projects out of the box. Completely independent solution.

All the other stuff in the spec is fine ... the cross service linking*, how we get the data out of the service, but the code change is too much, imho. 


* though, I would prefer to see something that unifies the cross-service Request-ID effort with this cross-service profiling effort. 

[1] https://github.com/ohthree/tach"}, {'account_id': 8688, 'date': '2015-01-07 13:34:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(25 comments)'}, {'account_id': 6172, 'date': '2015-01-07 13:46:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Sandy, 


I hate to say, but...

1) But your solution is not integrable. Like I can't integrate it via OpenStack API. It means that I am not able to integrate it with Rally or Horizon out of box. It means nobody will use it, cause it is too complicated. 

2) Monkey patching code requires non-stop rebasing -> nobody will do that -> non consumable stuff in real development

3) There is NO REAL LIFE CLIENTS (that pays money for OpenStack) that will allow you to restart all services on all servers and put monkey patching code EVEN IF IT IS absolutely safe. So your solution is not consumable in real life. 

4) POC results are that Tach is not commonly used and OpenStack have billions bottlenecks. 


5) LOGs and Notifications => They all have own purpose and are very useful in various cases. 
LOGs and Notifications => something that works for all requests, and get allow us to get some "common" data or understanding where something is failing. Profiling is useful when we are tuning some specific peace of OpenStack. In real life we need all that stuff.'}, {'account_id': 688, 'date': '2015-01-07 14:05:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Hmm, I think you may need to elaborate on some of these points for me:

1) But your solution is not integrable. Like I can't integrate it via OpenStack API. It means that I am not able to integrate it with Rally or Horizon out of box. It means nobody will use it, cause it is too complicated.

Not sure what you mean by "integrate it via OpenStack API"? And what's complicated about the solution?

2) Monkey patching code requires non-stop rebasing -> nobody will do that -> non consumable stuff in real development

It requires a config file change and only if the method/module changes. Possibly if the signature of the method changes, but that's easily handled. For common libraries like DB API or oslo.messaging, that's nearly never. 

3) There is NO REAL LIFE CLIENTS (that pays money for OpenStack) that will allow you to restart all services on all servers and put monkey patching code EVEN IF IT IS absolutely safe. So your solution is not consumable in real life.

If the requirement is to leave profiling on all the time, it can be done in the exact same manner osprofiler would do it. There's no difference, only in how the hook is applied. Putting a signal interface on it would be pretty simple, so the service would not have to be restarted. 

Requiring every project to take on the profiling effort seems like a big ask. We have a hard enough time getting everyone to standardize on logging and notification adoption as it is. 

That said, I can't imagine many companies wanting to leave profiling on all the time. There are much lower impact ways to gather metrics. Metering != instrumentation. 

4) POC results are that Tach is not commonly used and OpenStack have billions bottlenecks.

I agree that Tach is not commonly used, but the approach is. Not sure what you mean by "a billion bottlenecks"

5) LOGs and Notifications => They all have own purpose and are very useful in various cases. LOGs and Notifications => something that works for all requests, and get allow us to get some "common" data or understanding where something is failing. Profiling is useful when we are tuning some specific peace of OpenStack. In real life we need all that stuff.

I agree there is a place for it, but I don't think it's permanently in the code. Logs track processing, notifications track usage and events of interest to downstream consumers. Profiling, however, is done selectively and generally independently of production. It's largely just wrapping methods. It doesn't need to live in the code all the time. 

Side note: I think there is merit in trying to merge the notification and logging code. If there was some easy way to get the structured data. Perhaps the schema efforts will help there. 

Less code, not more code.'}, {'account_id': 688, 'date': '2015-01-07 14:17:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Ah, I think I get the "billions of bottlenecks" comment. 

Yes, there are. But, we find them, we squash them and we move on. The hook doesn't need to live in the code forever. I'd rather have  a separate config file and a test for regression checks.'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-01-15 11:21:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

(6 comments)

This is a problem that needs solving, agreed with that.

The cross service request-ids should be separated out from this effort, and made to work with logging. This is important regardless of profiling. Certainly I worry if profiling decides to use its own custom approach to the general problem.

The details of this are that it feels too intrusive on the projects you are profiling. I think with the use of something like https://github.com/ohthree/tach you can easily achieve your goals without having to touch the code in every project. The use of oslo should make it easy to monkey patch appropriate things to hook in the profiling, when required, trimming the list of active hook points to just what you are interested in.'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2015-01-23 00:22:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Ugh, my nice careful reply got eaten by the gerrit web UI and fat fingers.

So tl;dr:
 - noone wants to be playing catchup with trunk with their instrumentation. 
 - I support having the tracer (which this is, vs a profiler) be pluggable, *but* not at the cost of causing operators to play catchup.
 - If you haven't, please read http://research.google.com/pubs/pub36356.html which is about a very similar system. In particular note the ability to add additional trace messages from dev code: this is a feature, and one that the monkey patch approach doesn't offer, because it doesn't scale.
 - Yes logging is very similar. In fact one can build the same thing entirely out of logging if our messages are processable enough and enough effort is put into the log forwarding infrastructure; yet tach exists and that to me seems like evidence that its more pragmatic to use a direct service. That said, if we want to do it with logs, lets do that - keep the same API, have osprofiler push it into the logging subsystem. BUT: being able to sample is key, and one of the big differences between logging and tracing subsystems is that logging generally isn't a sampling based mechanism. Whereas a trace system is allowed to just drop events when a backlog builds up without blocking the thread or filling up disk.
 - good tracing is a feature. The time we spent implementing OOPS in Launchpad has been massively returned in fast diagnostics of operational issues - something I'm sure folk using tach or osprofiler have already experienced. It wasn't built for a distributed architecture, or I would have been proposing it or working on integration a few years back. That we don't offer this in the core by default is a reason for sadness IMO.

On intrusiveness, that I can agree with - if only we had a small number of pervasive layers that all potential things went through (see the dapper paper above :)). In fact I think we do have the opportunity to do that, though more layers are involved. But if we add tracing to oslo.messaging, all the server-used API clients, oslo.db and the REST framework that our APIs come in on, we should get excellent coverage (particularly when accompanied by judicious annotation of extra data."}, {'account_id': 688, 'date': '2015-01-28 18:22:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

If you're concerned about a mismatch between the monkey patch hooks and the code, this is a solved problem. We already do this with entry points, but it could just as easily be handled with a config file of mappings (which could be unit tested for accuracy). You're almost alluding to this in your last comment where the suggestion is to hook into the more pervasive layers. These layers rarely change. Even in the early days of openstack the rpc layers were quite stable. DB would be the same. The power of the monkey patching approach is it allows a deployer to insert ad-hoc patches without code changes. 

Not sure about your use of the word "scale" in your comment. Can you elaborate? It's been a long time since I read the Dapper doc, but I don't recall it saying anything about monkey patching nor it causing a scaling concern? I assume you're referring to my previous point?

Also, we're talking about the method of hooking into the system here, not what to do with the collected data. We could write it to a log or snail mail it to ops, but that's a handler/deployer decision. For profiling, my personal preference is a UDP message, since these are transient/non-mission critical updates. But let's focus on the hooks for now. 

As John said, the bigger discussion we should also have is dusting off the shared Request-ID's across services effort. That will pay big dividends to all these initiatives.'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-02-03 08:10:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(4 comments)'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-02-03 08:19:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

In all honesty; even though some of the questions keep on coming up again and again. I think we really need to start making some progress here... We've been 'flip flopping' (and debating) on this for years now and it makes me sorta sad that we can't just get something working and iterate (and stop trying to design the 'supreme' solution from the get-go); accept that we won't all have everything perfect, accept that it may not monkey-patch things in (and this is fine to disagree on IMHO) and move-on. I honestly believe not having something like this (and the endless debate around it) is actually hurting all of us more than we think/know...

My 2 cents..."}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2015-02-03 08:29:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Joshua, 

I think that not all of the questions here are as irrelevant as you're making them out to be. Monkey Patch vs non-Monkeypatch is a design choice that could be worked through in either case. Most of the concerns on overhead of a non-monkey patch model is something that could be quantified.

I don't think all the questions raise fall into perfect being the enemy of good.

This spec could be split into 2 distinct specs with clear wins on both fronts.

1) Unified request id. This seems non-controversial and should be easy to pass.
2) Profiling spec. While there are some concerns about "best approach", there are other questions that could be easily addressed without a complete re-architecture of the osprofiler.

So to get positive traction here I would like to see this spec split as outlined above. The profiling spec can focus on addressing [even if the answer is to clearly define where the hooks are instead of leaving it nebulous, which would mitigate some of the conversation around monkeypatching and overhead] the comments without a complete re-architecture. There are some things that block what I would accept into Keystone - but they wouldn't be extremely hard to fix (this revolves around the same comments from the original code proposal against keystone itself).'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-02-06 10:01:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Agree with Morgan that this could be split between the non-controversial part (cross-project request IDs) and the controversial part (best approach to profiling).'}, {'account_id': 6172, 'date': '2015-02-06 11:10:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Thanks everybody for comments. 

I think that this spec doesn't have enough good description of OSprofiler which produce a lot of debates.

I am going to update this spec soon to try to reply on all comments in review. Plus I will update "Alternative" section with Tach and request-id to make discussion more technical. 


By the way, actually I don't see any reason why I should split this spec to 2 different. The request-id mechanism is absolutely different thing for different purpose. 
request-id - is for adding ability to collect all log messages related to single request from various services. 

trace-id - is added for supporting nested points (that are useless in case of logs and most important part for tracing) 

I really don't see any reason to make a effort to combine this 2 absolutely different things together.'}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2015-02-06 20:19:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Boris,

Why do we need trace-ids that are independant of request ids? Could they be the same thing? Do we need another unique identifier for all requests or does it make sense to have them be the same? The win I see with them being the same is it allows an operator to see / correlate logs/audit-info/etc to profiling when run.

I still would advocate the split in this case for the reasons outlined. I am against having massive different numbers of ways to identify a request unless there is a very good reason these should be different identifiers ("because it would be easier to implement if they are different" is not the correct answer).'}, {'account_id': 6172, 'date': '2015-02-06 20:32:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Morgan,

It has absolutely different nature... It's similar to say "let's use Java in keystone Python and Java are close enough" 

request-id specify request (and it's not nested). 
trace-id specify point, 1 request creates N trace points. (points are nested)

So when we are building trace (by N trace points, even in single service), we are specifying all trace points by 3 trace ids: 
(base_trace_id, parent_point_trace, current_point_trace_id)

So trace-id doesn't care about request and doesn't specify request at all. (Actually if I don't gave up with this stuff I will work as well on tracing periodic task that are not triggered by REST at all)

2 different mechasim are required because: 
1) If we put to logs 3 uuids - the size of logs will be HUGE and we won't use these 3 uuids at all
2) If we don't have 3 uuids for describing trace point whole idea of osprofiler will be useless.'}, {'account_id': 688, 'date': '2015-02-06 20:34:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

yeah, request_id's aren't just for logging. We depend on them for notifications too. 

Couldn't trace-id be inferred from the stack (traceback)?"}, {'account_id': 688, 'date': '2015-02-06 20:41:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

specifically function_name:
https://docs.python.org/2/library/traceback.html#traceback.extract_tb'}, {'account_id': 8688, 'date': '2015-08-11 09:26:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

is this abandoned?'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2015-10-13 08:39:24.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

Boris, I'm abandoning this patch as the last comment from you is from 2015-02-7 and there are still several unaddressed comments. Feel free to restore it or ping me if you still want to pursue it."}]

commit_message:
Fix bug where clean steps do not run

A bug was introduced during Liberty where Ironic transparently
ignores all clean steps and finishes cleaning. This is caused
by _get_node_next_clean_steps returning an empty list when
cleaning has just started. Fix this method to return the full
list of clean steps when cleaning begins.

This may leave previous tenants' data on disk and available to future
tenants. Deployers should apply this patch (or upgrade to a new release
with this patch) ASAP.

Closes-Bug: #1517277
(cherry picked from commit 29eee264e0d111ab9ed1f7bb78276ea2eb2a59f5)

Change-Id: I9cfde767db126ef43f2c4f06ec455a3a736287cc

tag keystone 9.0.0.0b1 for mitaka-1

as per the instructions on the mailing list, we are now tracking
integrated projects in this repo. in setup.cfg, keystone had:
9.0.0, so we are tagging 9.0.0.0b1 for mitaka-1.

review to remove version from setup.cfg:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/252078/

Release Heat 6.0.0b1

Per the new process [1], we now need to tag milestones. Here is the
6.0.0b1 release for the Heat project.

[1]
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-November/080692.html

Henry, I am curious what is wrong with it in the first place.  You say it doesn't adhere to the standards [1].  does that mean he should be assigning the dictionary inside the log and the exception like [2]? 

[1] https://bugs.launchpad.net/keystone/+bug/1443912

[2] http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.i18n/guidelines.html#adding-variables-to-log-messages"}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2015-11-24 15:29:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Tom....I'm saying that the original code looks OK to me (in terms of translator-friendly-ness)..."}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2015-11-24 15:42:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Ok, putting my hand up here...I goofed with raising this as a bug! While the guidance is that you should normally pass the substitution elements into the LOG call (so that we are only doing the substitution work if we are logging at that level), given that we are also using that message as an exception, it is better to do the substitution as it is now.'}, {'account_id': 17860, 'date': '2015-11-26 18:34:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 10046, 'date': '2015-12-02 18:24:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

isn't this the case to use _LW?"}, {'account_id': 17123, 'date': '2015-12-02 19:28:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

I think this looks good to go once the commit message is updated.  Should that bug be tagged invalid?

@Henrique you aren't suppose to use _LW in the case.  Check out this example:
http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.i18n/guidelines.html#choosing-a-marker-function"}, {'account_id': 8866, 'date': '2015-12-03 14:55:03.000000000', 'content': "Abandoned

commit_message:
Translation-friendly formatting of msg string

The token controller doesn't adhere to the guidance for string translations.

We fix the string translation keep the log pattern on Keystone.

We add a new log entry for a similar error in the same method.

Change-Id: I60a7a34070a51d3ab186d685c056e8a68460022d
Closes-Bug: #1443912

commit_message:
Code refactoring - Watcher Applier package

This patchset is there to change the code structure.
The objective is to flatten the project file tree by merging
'api/' and 'framework/' into a single package. This also contains
some tidy ups in package naming (like using only singular nouns).

This should only affect file/folder names and their subsequent
import paths wherever they were used.

Change-Id: Id7b37667c613086d8ef3cd1f367c4219bf026fc7

Making all names URL-safe will allow us to pick a character to be the separator of project names, # for example. This way, we could do parent#child#grandchild when requesting a token by project name.

If this isn't why we are introducing these checks for url-safe, I don't know what that buy us."}, {'account_id': 8978, 'date': '2015-11-24 09:56:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

At the last keystone meeting [0], this patch was well supported by the core team and received one negative vote. Though the latest spec addresses that comment by providing a configuration option (off/new/strict).

[0] http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/keystone/2015/keystone.2015-12-01-18.01.html'}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2015-12-03 09:02:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

(2 comments)

So have discussed this with morgan. The alternative to saying that the name can only contain unreserved characters, is to say that it must not contain any reserved characters (which is what the spec used to say). The difference is that later does not preclude unicode, the former does.  However, doing just the later wouldn't (I think) make searching and authoring using unicode naming magically work - we'd have to add support for somehow encode/decoding it so you could so something like GET /projects?name=%88%F8%82%AB%8A%84%82%E8.  

Since the reserved chars in http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc3986 are encoded the  same in unicode as ascii, this doesn't actually affect our goal of ensuring the we have delimiters reserved so that we can move to a url naming scheme.  So I'm ok reverting the spec to say that we will simple preclude the reserved characters.  This means that any customer using unicode can "go strict" straight away, even though we have more work to do (and part of a separate bp) to allow them to do things like url naming in the future. Any objections?'}, {'account_id': 5707, 'date': '2015-12-03 09:04:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Sean Perry - you kindly commented on the difference between reserved and unreserved in a previous version of this spec - any comment on this?'}, {'account_id': 2218, 'date': '2015-12-03 14:36:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-12-03 14:37:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: -Verified

commit_message:
Allow url-safe project and domain names to be optionally enforced

In preparation for future support for hierarchical naming of projects and
domains, deprecate non url-safe names as well as optionally enforce
url-safe names.

Co-Authored-By: Adam Young <ayoung@redhat.com>

Blueprint url-safe-naming
Change-Id: I00c43a542b915695be025a288e8387358e1277ea

commit_message:
Remove py26 support from designate

as of mitaka, the infra team won't have the resources available to
reasonably test py26, also the oslo team is dropping py26 support
from their libraries. sine we rely on oslo for a lot of our work,
and depend on infra for our CI, we should drop py26 support too.

Change-Id: I4aeba7269ddb465ac61f851f5b5d2ab1b91882e4
Related-Bug: #1519510

commit_message:
Make all network ports type to consume FixedIPs

This change adds to the internal_api, storage, storage_mgmt and
tenant network ports the FixedIPs param and make them consume it
when passed.

Change-Id: Ica2bca9f573b206cc60c9d572224a8cc7b9b8aa4

commit_message:
Fix postgresql manifest

Remove hardcoded postgresql version and paths because they broke
installation in CentOS7

Is compatible with CentOS6 master node

Implements: blueprint master-on-centos7

Change-Id: I660c4aa402188e1b089eab14f9478e3baa30310c
Co-Authored-By: Sergii Golovatiuk <sgolovatiuk@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Updating tests for openstack-ansible-security

This patch adds a framework for testing the role with check mode as well as a
fully functional test that secures a system.  The two new tests will be
enabled by default when the check mode improvements are merged and some common
playbook failures are removed.

Closes-bug: 1521229

Change-Id: Iaffb982c4c9776bcc4b219e257d83591d58d0cee

add network awareness to the physical functions passthough
by associating it with a Neutron port.

commit_message:
Enable SR-IOV physical functions assignment with Neutron port

Relying on the sriov-physical-function-passthrough spec
add network awareness to the physical functions passthough
by associating it with a Neutron port.

Implements blueprint sriov-pf-passthrough-neutron-port

Change-Id: I9aebc1bce867916f5bf5b5139850b67a151da123

    pip install docker-py==1.2.0'}, {'account_id': 14027, 'date': '2015-12-02 15:10:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Hui: It's not needed. Passing Docker API version as a kwarg of docker-py resolved the compatibility issues for us, really. We checked that and works fine.

We don't want to pin version of docker-py, because when Artur did it in the previous patchset, it violated global requirements.

Also, why 1.2.0? Before 30 Nov we used 1.5.0 and worked out of the box. In the 1.6.0 version this change is needed."}, {'account_id': 19542, 'date': '2015-12-02 15:13:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Patch Set 2 don't change anything in docker-py installation process, it set only in communication layer client-api version to be not newer than  api used in docker 1.8.2. In requirements.txt is still docker-py>=1.4.0"}, {'account_id': 18652, 'date': '2015-12-02 15:13:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 16993, 'date': '2015-12-02 15:15:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hi, Artur, thanks for the info.

In the log posted with the bug, it shows 

raise errors.APIError(e, response, explanation=explanation)
APIError: 400 Client Error: Bad Request ("client is newer than server (client API version: 1.21, server API version: 1.20)")

Are they different?'}, {'account_id': 19542, 'date': '2015-12-02 15:26:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

In kolla project docker version is fixed to 1.8.2. This docker version use api 1.20. Two days ago was release docker-py version 1.6.0 and it use 1.21 api version as default. When server api version < client api version, then we get error like:client is newer than server  (client API version: 1.21, server API version: 1.20)
So there are two solutions: 
1) fix everywhere docker-py version >=1.4.0 and <1.6.0 (patch set 1) but we can't make this 
2) change the api version used by client to < than server api version (patch set 2) and then we can stay only with requirements docker-py >=1.4.0 as it was previously"}, {'account_id': 14027, 'date': '2015-12-02 15:26:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

@Hui: yes, these versions are different. Docker-py assumes the  higher API version of server than Docker 1.8.2 uses. That's why we have to use the older API.

If you have doubts why we have Docker pinned to 1.8.2 - that's because of Ansible which is not working with higher versions."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-12-02 15:32:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-12-02 11:24:22.000000000', 'message': '[Verify] Fixing failures of test_server_basicops

In order to fix the test_server_basicops test we can add "cirros" to
the name of a cirros image that will be uploaded to the cloud. Or we
can configure the ssh_user_regex option [1], which is more complecated.
So this patch adds "cirros" to the name of the cirros image. Also this
patch explisitly sets the ssh_user_regex option to the default value
to allow users to configure this option when they use their own image.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/tempest/blob/master/tempest/config.py#L1215

Change-Id: I94abe3ae8738e322472dae78796ff36c4d6132ba
'}, {'created': '2015-12-02 11:28:19.000000000', 'message': '[Verify] Fixing failures of test_server_basicops

In order to fix the test_server_basicops test we can add "cirros" to
the name of a cirros image that will be uploaded to the cloud. Or we

commit_message:
[Verify] Fixing failures of test_server_basicops

This patch is intended to fix the following error:

testtools.matchers._impl.MismatchError: u'172.24.5.204' != "Please login as 'cirros' user, not as root\n\n"

In order to fix the test_server_basicops test we can add "cirros" to
the name of a cirros image that will be uploaded to the cloud. Or we
can configure the ssh_user_regex option [1], which is more complicated.
So this patch adds "cirros" to the name of the cirros image. Also this
patch explicitly sets the ssh_user_regex option to the default value
to allow users to configure this option when they use their own image.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/tempest/blob/master/tempest/config.py#L1215

Change-Id: I94abe3ae8738e322472dae78796ff36c4d6132ba

commit_message:
Move store config opt to glance_store section

Store config options under DEFAULT section have been marked deprecated
and moved to glance_store section. With glance_store 0.10.0, the
deprecated options have been dropped, which causes the scrubber tests
to fail as they still have filesystem_store_datadir under DEFAULT section.
So, moving it under glance_store section here.

Closes-Bug: 1522132

Change-Id: If5c11a2b616d3e0b577de34cc0286b18adc327c2

commit_message:
Remove HTTPAccept exception from node update API

Node update API returns 202 to client now, so HTTPAccept exception
should be removed.
Due to api-wg UPDATE method should return a response body,
add TODO for it.

Change-Id: I910fd3813a4a0542075766e560112a44cdaaca03
Closes-bug: #1522291
partial-blueprint: http-response-modification

commit_message:
Remove HTTPAccept exception raised when update cluster

Cluster update API return 202 to client now, so HTTPAccept
exception should be removed.
Due to api-wg UPDATE method should return a response body
and resource url in response header. Add TODO for it.

Change-Id: I60f47300b454a5c45cbb62593475e78b1bd862a6
Closes-bug: #1522289
partial-blueprint: http-response-modification

[{'created': '2015-12-03 03:09:36.000000000', 'message': "Merge cluster/node list test to other test cases

Currently, cluster/node list test cases expect an empty list as
correct test result. This makes them easily to be broken by other
failed test case which leaves obsolete cluster/node resource. Also,
it's unnecessary to define individual test cases for cluster/node
list. This patch addresses these issues by merging cluster/node list
tests into other test cases.

commit_message:
Merge cluster/node list test to other test cases

Currently, cluster/node list test cases expect an empty list as
correct test result. This makes them easily to be broken by other
failed test case which leaves obsolete cluster/node resource. Also,
it's unnecessary to define individual test cases for cluster/node
list. This patch addresses these issues by merging cluster/node list
tests into other test cases.

Change-Id: I04849fc74dfcbea87eb767352b9e4bd23b4f8ef5

commit_message:
Change data precision of action.start_time and action.end_time

This patch changes data precision of action.start_time and
action.end_time to Float('24,8') to avoid incorrect time value
truncation.

Change-Id: Idff39350485f3fc1612e08a2146e84ed57486bb8
Closed-Bug: #1522296

commit_message:
setUp/tearDown decorator for set/clear override

Problem with recursion shows up only in full runs
of Nova for example. So split the code that sets
up the decorator and add a method to cleanup
the decorated set_override during teardown.

Also add a decorator for clear_override similar to
the one for set_override.

Added more tests for all the above.

Change-Id: Ib16af2e770e96d971aef7f5c5d48ffd781477cfe

commit_message:
Optimize "open" method with context manager

Replace the classic open() method with opening context
manager to open file so that the file will be closed
even if an exception occurs.

Change-Id: I0d53b7a38fee6a2ef8ce74496d220adc954afb98

commit_message:
Add more maintainers to Nailgun

We have just three maintainers in Nailgun.
More maintainers is required to make review more effective.
And Bulat is excelent candidate to be a maintainer here.
Please look at: http://stackalytics.com/report/contribution/fuel-web/30 and
http://stackalytics.com/report/contribution/fuel-web/90

Change-Id: I294775e44f2dd3348c9b50044c8b1d066d61e9f1

commit_message:
Updated the py_pkgs lookup plugin for multi source

The py_pkgs lookup plugin will now handle multiple sources. This change
was needed to enable the system to allow for overrides of repo_package
resources and general python packaging as found throughout the stack.
The module has precedence as it loads / searches for packages and he item
loaded last is the one that has the most precedence.

The repo-build play has been updated to now search for compatible packages
in the main playbook directory, the root ansible role directory and the
user_variables file.

Documentation has been added regarding this capability and how to override
and set items to meet the needs of the deployment.

Closes-Bug: #1510575
Implements: blueprint independent-role-repositories
Change-Id: Ib7cda14db18c0ca58bb5ac495d1c201812cf0f48
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kevin.carter@rackspace.com>

commit_message:
Removed py26 support

as of mitaka, the infra team won't have the resources available to
reasonably test py26, also the oslo team is dropping py26 support from
their libraries. sine we rely on oslo for a lot of our work, and depend
on infra for our CI, we should drop py26 support too.

Change-Id: I8aec07a1149ad7232c3d6db2f3c274ec9ce11a66
Closes-Bug: #1522363

commit_message:
Remove py26 support

As of mitaka, the infra team won't have the resources available to
reasonably test py26, also the oslo team is dropping py26 support
from their libraries. sine we rely on oslo for a lot of our work,
and depend on infra for our CI, we should drop py26 support too.
Closes-Bug: 1519510

Change-Id: I72b6e6cb881f3ce34b61020c0b6614de8335badd

commit_message:
nova: set catalog_info to InternalURL

In nova.conf, set cinder/catalog_info to 'volumev2:cinderv2:internalURL'
instead of 'volumev2:cinderv2:publicURL'.
So Nova will use internal Cinder endpoint to reach volume API by
using internal network.

Change-Id: Ia34f0fe59f662c3ad29ca0178c01ef1570759d57
(cherry picked from commit c66c5c6ff8346963940b3f5623c7cf5d5fb9df61)

commit_message:
Make puppet manifests compliant with Puppet 4.x

- https://docs.puppetlabs.com/puppet/3.8/reference/deprecated_language.html
- Temporary disablement of the pupppet-lint autoload layout check
  failing for ringbuilder.pp. A fix for that will be part of an other patch.

Conflicts:
	puppet/manifests/overcloud_controller_pacemaker.pp

(conflict due to not backporting b60e8f79)

Change-Id: I495825641ab12e7c5789c1405649c356c5bb8051
Signed-off-by: Gael Chamoulaud <gchamoul@redhat.com>
(cherry picked from commit b9aab0951835be1acee0e116b0d679c9af1489f4)

commit_message:
Do not enforce start timeout to 90s for neutron-server

The same timeout value is set for every pcmk service in [1]

1. https://github.com/openstack/tripleo-heat-templates/blob/master/puppet/manifests/overcloud_controller_pacemaker.pp#L81

(cherry picked from commit 7093465bcd718b62789fe9fd37948ef217e7a55e)

commit_message:
Fix dependency for Ceilometer agent when using MySQL

In HA, when using MySQL as a backend for Ceilometer, the dependencies
set for the Ceilometer central agent depended always on MongoDB; Which
should only be the case if MongoDB is set as a backend.

Change-Id: I6fecfe0564b13e9352313c5a3492505b44d12eaa
(cherry picked from commit e4ac0fcb9d705aae112145b52e19cf7d0266c7f4)

commit_message:
Support NFS backend for Glance (via Pacemaker)

Adds support for NFS backend in Glance by allowing the storage directory
for the 'file' backend to be a mount managed by Pacemaker. Default
behavior is unchanged.

Since the Pacemaker-related parameters are not exposed on top level,
change storage-environment.yaml to use parameter_defaults instead of
parameters.

Depends on a Heat fix for environment file's parameter_defaults to
work well with JSONs and comma delimited lists (see Depends-On).

Change-Id: I6e7e2eaf6919b955650c0b32e1629a4067602c89
Depends-On: I85b13a79dbc97a77e20c0d5df8eaf05b3000815e
(cherry picked from commit 3729e63b59b36615180e64ffdab9e1f6fd66796e)

Add Puppet 4.x lint checks

- This change adds Puppet-lint bits for checking Puppet manifests.

Change-Id: I82869d8f9f6c64ac2a95429f453c3cb76c046974
Signed-off-by: Gael Chamoulaud <gchamoul@redhat.com>
(cherry picked from commit 0d6b04c21a8308701416c15c1594d6253d848753)

commit_message:
Sync httpd vhost settings in between pcmk and non-pcmk scenarios

Moves the vhost_params out of the manifest and into static hiera;
also removes unneeded server_alias parameter as that matched the
vhost servername anyway.

Change-Id: I4b5971b23ef3be9529a59075fa93ccc64af75b9c
(cherry picked from commit 6c6384e901f6e5925ed69738683cf5849d85b7d4)

Fix tests for image-create

image-create unit tests still checks for obsolete v1 params --location
and --copy-from

remove checking of these params

Closes-bug: 1521044

commit_message:
Ensure memcached resource uses interleave=true

Without interleave Pacemaker will consider memcached as a single
unit on all nodes so it will restart dependencies on every node in
case of failures.

More info at: https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1262425

Depends-On: I23c3e7ada3da8085957e86406527e9e5202bdd69
Change-Id: I284cbf33c8453a2abefc862f3d2e0b7f11ff4c3d
(cherry picked from commit b892ca4705282fe3b857a5eaa7c0f0c8a944d36e)

commit_message:
Fix nova_virt_type auto-detection

In https://review.openstack.org/243098 nova_virt_type auto-detection
was implemented, but the default nova_virt_type value of kvm was left
in place, resulting in the auto-detection never happening.

This patch implements the auto-detection if nova-virt_type is not set
and removes the default value for nova-virt_type.

Change-Id: Ic1c8f042bc6bbee542373d335f338866efa06dc7

commit_message:
Fixed doc generation warning

The BaseStrategy interface was moved to another location but the
documentation wasn't updated accordingly, so here I updated this
import path.
As an extra, I also updated the description of the Solution which
also had an outdated import path.

Closes-Bug: #1522034

Hi, Michael Still	
 
 here is the libvirt doc string about detachDeviceFlags.
 http://paste.openstack.org/show/480330/
 
 it says 
 To check whether the device was successfully removed, either recheck domain
 configuration using virDomainGetXMLDesc() or add handler for
 VIR_DOMAIN_EVENT_ID_DEVICE_REMOVED

 If so we  can sync check by virDomainGetXMLDesc().
 Or async notification that the device is removed by an event handler.

 and this is the nova code about detach_interface.
 https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/compute/manager.py#L4940

 for sync recheck, we can change the code as follow:

 # as the libvirt suggests: use virDomainGetXMLDesc()
 def detach_interface(self, context, instance, port_id):
    ...
    # just pseudo-code
    # user maybe have detached the device, 
    # but the device finally detached after timeout. 
    #  maybe this is retry: 
    if not(virDomainGetXMLDesc()): 
       if get_port():
           self.network_api.deallocate_port_for_instance()
       return

    self.driver.detach_interface(instance, condemned)

    for i in range(1, 51):
       if not(virDomainGetXMLDesc()):
            sleep(1)
        else if i == 51：
            raise exception("please retry to detach the interface.")
        else:
            break
    self.network_api.deallocate_port_for_instance()'}, {'account_id': 14131, 'date': '2015-12-02 10:54:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Hi, Michael Still

 This is another spec of the sync check solution by virDomainGetXMLDesc()
 http://paste.openstack.org/show/480601/'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2015-12-02 11:04:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

I'm not really convinced this is something that should use the spec process. This is really a bug fix to the libvirt driver."}, {'account_id': 14131, 'date': '2015-12-02 12:23:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

hi Daniel Berrange.

 1. If we use the sync check by virDomainGetXMLDesc(), it can a bug fix.

 2. But add handler for VIR_DOMAIN_EVENT_ID_DEVICE_REMOVED, maybe we need add a async mechanism, this seems complex. 
 We need to notify the volume/interface detach caller when the handler receive the event.

 not sure which do you prefer？1 or 2?      
 
 and here is more details about this solution.
 http://paste.openstack.org/show/480617/'}, {'account_id': 5441, 'date': '2015-12-02 16:00:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

I agree that this doesn't really need a spec.  What might justify a spec is an async mechanism for event processing but there's no information here on why that is necessary.  Why can't the event be handled synchronously like syncing power states is?"}, {'account_id': 14131, 'date': '2015-12-03 02:28:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Andrew Laski

 async mechanism, we need to filter the event. 
 maybe the user unplug in 2 device.

 We need to filter which is we need. 

 it is different with power states. 

 now I will file a bug, and sync recheck by virDomainGetXMLDesc()

 any suggestion?'}, {'account_id': 14131, 'date': '2015-12-03 13:11:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

file a bug https://bugs.launchpad.net/nova/+bug/1522400'}, {'account_id': 14131, 'date': '2015-12-03 13:12:05.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

file a bug.'}]

Anyway the spec needs rework to reflect decisions made at the Summit."}, {'account_id': 14119, 'date': '2015-11-04 00:41:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

I was unable to attend the Cinder sessions in question and I admittedly am not that familiar with the Cinder code, only going so far as to write a plugin at one point in time.

Can you give a summary of what is expected to change in this spec that was influenced by summit conversations? Will the general idea change or just the technical implementation?'}, {'account_id': 11600, 'date': '2015-11-04 14:24:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

@Sam: It's more like technical implementation details. Mainly we want to skip automatic resource cleanup part, as it introduces a lot of complexity and whole process is a little risky. We may revisit the idea later.

Also the outcome of cross-project DLM session is that OpenStack projects may have hard requirement on DLM software (through Tooz). This simplifies driver locks part and gives us possibility to replace manager locks with Tooz as first step. DLM like ZooKeeper would be required only in case of running A/A and in the future we still intend to remove manager locks somehow."}, {'account_id': 14119, 'date': '2015-11-04 23:50:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

@Michal

commit_message:
Simplified boolean variable check

Currently 'self.cells' is being checked
for empty list like 'if self.cells == []:'.
The more standard approach is like 'if not self.cells:'.

TrivialFix

Change-Id: I681e11c13696f3e85c3598838ac5ed33c378de3f

(1 comment)

So i wondered how to test this, because i never hit the real issue with heat stack timing out on my enverinment. So i tried manually editing the 'timeout_mins' in heat DB to 99 instead of 240, then `heat stack-show overcloud | grep timeout` showed 99. Then i ran the update command, and it still showed 99 for the duration of the update, but after the update completed, it showed 240 again. So i guess the value did get to Heat, but it was updated in the database after the operation completed. What that means for the actual effective timeout of the update itself i'm not sure, but if there's some further fix required for the timeout to propagate correctly, it would probably have to be done in Heat itself."}, {'account_id': 8042, 'date': '2015-12-01 17:52:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Confirmed, i updated the value in tripleo-common manually to 250 to see if it will get propagated, and it did, again i saw the output in stack-show only after the whole operation completed.'}, {'account_id': 9712, 'date': '2015-12-02 09:36:36.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-12-02 09:43:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

The same thing is actually in the scale.py file :) But it doesn't matter that much."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-12-02 16:34:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

>  What that means for the actual effective timeout of the update itself i'm not sure

The timeout passed via the API should be used, the fact that stack-show doesn't show the new timeout until the stack is stored at the end of the update is a quirk of the implementation (or maybe could be considered a bug).

But Heat should use the new value, e.g if the pre-update stack has timeout_mins of 1 and you pass timeout_mins of 100 in the update API request, Heat should use 100 on update."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-12-02 17:44:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Set a default timeout for 240 minutes for Heat Updates

This matches the behaviour in python-tripleoclient and helps us
avoid Heat timing out the update.

Change-Id: Iae80be66338f88b85b6df7a45055ea84cb5f47b0

Again, the patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/233043/ which impacts manila_tempest_tests has been merged, so in order to test this patch, we need to checkout latest tempest code or at least some commit which includes change 233043.'}, {'account_id': 16643, 'date': '2015-11-28 14:47:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Sam, 

Please check out: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/243233/

In this patch, we moved some portions of contrib/ci/pre_test_hook.sh to contrib/ci/common.sh. One of the things moved was the Tempest Commit that the gate checks out to run all the manila tests. Manila's gate jobs are never run on the latest version of tempest.. we stick with a "stable commit" and upgrade from time to time to avoid constant breakages.  

If you look at this file: https://github.com/openstack/manila/blob/14d57d1/contrib/ci/common.sh

You will notice that our gate is currently checking out  c43c8f91 (And this "upgrade" was made on 5th Nov 2015).. 

So if your code depends on a tempest commit that was made on Nov 18th 2015 in Tempest, (https://github.com/openstack/tempest/commit/bf57df1c4fefdafbf4f099e97341023e3e8ce505), you should update the commit hash in contrib/ci/common.sh. Unless you update that file, tests here will continue to fail because your code refers to classes that were not there in tempest's c43c8f91.'}, {'account_id': 8851, 'date': '2015-11-28 14:51:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Change manila_tempest_tests to use credentials_factory

With the merge of 'Factor up config dependent credential classes' in tempest,
(Change-Id: I351f86f0570070105bbf24f2d904e917feea6e57)
helper methods related to credentials have been moved to
common.credentials_factory module.
manila_tempest_tests need to change accordingly.

Change-Id: I9e5c72279638e07f509a4bfe0174b5ad5ee70b45
Closes-Bug: #1519612

commit_message:
Increate try_sleep to 10 for Galera wait-initial-sync

Deployment can fail under high load due to slow MySQL start.

Change-Id: I491f4eed6c12b960f34f1b0ce45d72c62f48ab60
Closes-Bug: 1522350

and that is incompatible with pylint 1.4.4. To prevent breakage,
we are pinning astroid to 1.3.8 on kilo branch (and pinning pylint
to 1.4.4).

It is expected that pylint will not be updated on this branch.

commit_message:
Fix pylint breakage for kilo branch

Using test-requirements.txt to pin pylint to 1.4.4 and astroid to
less than 1.4.0, as newer versions break pylint. Doesn't apply to
liberty or newer, as they use constraints, which limit version.

It is expected that pylint will not be updated on this branch.

Change-Id: I417207a067b4f235ab6ddd479a5092505d63479f
Partial-Bug: #1521766

commit_message:
fix functional gate

new keystone libs are breaking the functional tests. it seems
keystonemiddleware is implicitly being loaded when calling
prepare_service. we don't really need to call this so let's see
if it changes anything if we stop calling it.

Closes-Bug: #1522166
